{"blocks":[{"key":"3m2s2","text":"Before starting, I will typically put the specimens in numerical order, which includes adding my own lab/herbarium code to the specimens. This makes the final digital spreadsheet preparation much easier. Having the samples in order allows the final spreadsheet to be populated by drag-and-drop in Excel and it allows all of the iNat numbers to be copy and pasted (always with some minor modification) directly into the final sample spreadsheet. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7k9r0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9ki72","text":"As an example, I will lay out all of my samples, mark the bags with a lab code (ex - 1 to 96) and enter the same lab code into the iNat Voucher number(s) observational field (Ex - OSF2022-096). I then pull tissue from the samples in that order, filling the cells from right to left across the strip.  (Loading right to left allows the flow to go from A -\u003e H of a typical 96-well plate style format.)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9tvm0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"lmsa","text":"This takes some time initially, but it will save time with later with spreadsheet preparation. It typically takes me 15-30 minutes to fully populate the final spreadsheet with this prep-work. It would otherwise take several hours. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2gd5h","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7ulo","text":"The ultimate methodology you utilize will depend on the types of samples you are processing, the format of the voucher numbers, and the location of the metadata/images. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4g3u3","text":"Once all of the strips on the plate have X-amp, tap down each strip with your finger to ensure there are no air bubbles in the bottom of the tube underneath the liquid and that the tissue is completely submerged in the fluid. Spin down each strip for 10 seconds in a mini centrifuge. As you pull them out, once again, ensure the tissue in each cell is in the fluid. It is ok if a sample is too large for the amount of fluid and only partially submerged.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1gf0a","text":"Optional: Microwave the samples for 2 minutes. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"avt5e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6lbe5","text":"This template is now ready for use in PCR reactions.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
